Joe Clayton's Diadem series comprises seven novels so far.

06:46.600 --> 06:52.500
These are Diadem from the Stars, Lamarcos, Ursud, Maeve, Star Hunters, The Nowhere Hunt, and Ghost Hunt.

06:52.740 --> 06:57.380
Clayton's settings are well done, the action is exciting, and her characters are deep and believable.

06:57.820 --> 07:02.720
In fact, the series is carried by the protagonist, Elidas, who is on a quest to uncover her heritage.

07:03.220 --> 07:07.420
We were curious how the series got started. Did Clayton conceive of Elidas or the Diadem first?

07:07.420 --> 07:10.960
Well, Elidas was the character first to growl.

07:12.280 --> 07:20.520
Actually, the first image that hit me was that first page of the first book.

07:21.460 --> 07:35.120
I just got this feeling for something suddenly and breaking into the world that she knew.

07:35.120 --> 07:38.020
The crash of the ship was the thief.

07:39.600 --> 07:44.840
He was also one of the first characters that came up with. I could see him in his flight.

07:45.840 --> 07:52.120
Well, I see these things. Once I get to know them, I'm a very visual person.

07:53.160 --> 07:56.640
There's this little movie screen in the front of my head that goes through.

07:56.640 --> 08:01.580
But those are the things that came first of all.

08:03.120 --> 08:06.880
The picture of the thief in flight, I didn't know what he had stolen.

08:07.660 --> 08:11.000
The crashing on the wall, I didn't know what that crash meant.

08:12.840 --> 08:17.240
And slowly building up complications. I like complications.

08:28.020 --> 08:33.460
When Warren reads the Diadem series sequentially, he sees the continuing evolution of Clayton's writing style.

08:33.860 --> 08:37.380
Yes. For instance, the first novel carefully explains the concept of the Diadem.

08:37.660 --> 08:42.740
The alien artifact containing three trapped human spirits. It also covers how Elidas learned to draw power from it.

08:42.920 --> 08:47.680
But in the later novels, the Diadem more or less takes a backseat to other issues. Here Clayton comments.

08:48.800 --> 08:54.860
I also am thinking of the series as my workshop in education and writing.

08:55.620 --> 09:01.300
And the concepts I might have had in the beginning. I'm not going to stick with them.

09:01.920 --> 09:06.200
I'll modify the vastness areas. I learned more about my craft.

09:11.000 --> 09:17.360
More and more, in the last books, I hope the character of the people trapped in the Diadem.

09:17.360 --> 09:28.080
Is coming through. And as they come out, achieve re-embodied, or whatever you want to call it.

09:29.260 --> 09:34.760
They become more and more real to me and more important than the Diadem itself.

09:35.680 --> 09:41.380
Elidas is a very tough, strong character. This happened partly because of Clayton's experience in dealing with teenagers as a teacher.

09:41.920 --> 09:45.580
She consequently had to place Elidas in situations where even her powers would be tested.

09:45.580 --> 09:50.340
I said before that I was in a situation where I was really banging my head against the wall.

09:51.560 --> 09:57.800
I was teaching English, you know, and while this is very important, there were so many things happening to my kids.

09:58.380 --> 10:08.020
I guess I got too involved with them. That I was totally helpless to alleviate things that, you know,

10:08.020 --> 10:12.700
the pressures on them, the wounds that they got from them, the world around them.

10:13.520 --> 10:18.620
That I was just absolutely useless in helping them live through.

10:21.540 --> 10:34.020
I created perhaps a character that was in the end a little bit too powerful, too able to go to a world magic or way out of things.

10:34.020 --> 10:40.320
So I had to create problems for her and help her come to an understanding of the limitations of power.

10:40.760 --> 10:48.820
Which I guess is one of the themes in what I'm writing.

